Syifa is the cake shop's owner's daughter. She helps her mother managing the little shop between her classes. Stella and Sarah are regulars who always swing by whenever they have free time and money. They usually order absurd amount of cakes and somehow manage to finish all of them. When she has no other customer to tend to, Syifa will join them. The three of them bond over their love for sweet foods, especially cakes. They never really talk about their own lifes with each other, but that's fine for them. It feels nice to talk about nothing but their favorite foods. And when their weights increase the next day, no one complains.

The first time the petals made their presence known was a week after he was gone. The dark blue petals softly fluttered down, their color stood out starkly against the white tiles of her bathroom's floor. The sight made her laughed shakily, which resulted in her being doubled over her, their, sink once again, a fresh stream of dark blue flown out of her mouth.

Blue. Iris. Her namesake. Faith.

She knew she only had two options. It had been drilled into her head ever since she was young. A surgery to remove the ever-blooming flowers in her chest, with the consequence of forgetting her feelings for him, or having her feelings be reciprocated. 
She laughed. Both of them were impossible. She'd rather die if that means she wouldnt have to forget, and how can a dead man love her back? "You did this to me, you moron," she whispered softly, watching as the last petal fell onto her palm.

A little bit context: Hanahaki byou is a fictional disease which made people vomit flower petals when they experience unrequited love. It's dangerous if it's not treated immediately, since the petals can clog your respiratory system. They are only two known cure. The first is a surgery to remove the flowers from said person, but they will also lose their feelings along with the flowes. The second is having their love reciprocated.

Also, I know, they're not irises. I can't draw flowers. Just deal with it?

[Homesick]

Olivia saw the picture when she visited the orphanage. It was crudely drawn in red and green and blue crayons, pinned onto the fridge among the orphaned kids pictures with equally bright-colored magnets. She guessed one of the younger kids had drawn them, and,  being a big softie she was, the caretaker decided to pin it there for all to see.

Olivia traced the outline of the drawing, the paper felt crisp under her fingertips. Her rich brown eyes landed on a simple word written in stiff letters under the picture.

Home.

The four-lettered word sent a twinge of sadness to her heart and Olivia found herself longing for it. It was true that she was happy now. She had great friends and collegues, a place to stay, a steady income, other places and people she could call her homes. And yet none of them felt like her first home.

None of them smelt like her mother's chocolate chips and perfumes. None of them sounded like her father's bellowing laughter.  None of them looked as bright as her brother's room in a summer day. None of then were as gentle as her mother's smile, as kind as her father's words, as lovely as her brother's humming voice. It wasn't perfect, but, in her opinion, her first home was the best thing she could ask for.

And yet an explosion took it all away. It took her mother's calming voice, it took her father's calloused hands, it took her brother's soft hair.

And now, years later, under the roof of one of her many homes, Olivia felt incredibly homesick.

Rei has forgotten his way home. "Run," his mother had simply answered when he asked her what he should do when she's gone. And so he did. He runs, runs, runs, for days, months, years. He runs and keeps on running, losing himself in this maze of a city. So lost he can no longer remember how to go back. Not like he can, anyway. (After all, freezing to death on the road  is much better than being sold to dirty-minded old men)

He found Mei and Marcell later, or rather, they found him. They were running too, and still running, even now. They stick together ever since, surviving is much easier when they're together. Acting as a family, trusting no one but each other, huddling together for warmth.

Everything sucks, but they are happy. (Yet they still haven't found their way home)

Promt: lost

[No one knows what lies behind The Queen of Hearts' mask]

Hiding her real identity is in her job's descriptions. To present herself as another individual, to display only emotions which will work for her favor. Her real name, her personality, her hobby, all of it was carefully interwined in fabricated lies. (The biggest lie is the one which has an ounce of truth behind it, after all)

And she enjoys it. She enjoys the secrecy. She enjoys hiding everything behind her perfectly crafted mask. She enjoys the shocked expression her targets make when they finally understand who they are dealing with. She enjoys the sweet, swret lies which dripped free from her tongue. [They said The Queen of Hearts is a born liar]

Prompt: Hidden

Looking at the display in front of her, she finds it hard to believe that three years ago, eating something as delicious as a cake was nothing more than a pipe dream. That three years ago, she had to survive on nothing more than left-overs her mother remembered to bring home. That three years ago, hunger was her constant company.

Sometime, she still has to pinch herself to make sure she isn't dreaming when she sees the inside of the Quarter's fridge, which is always filled with everyone's favorite food. The fact that, yes, she can eat all of those foods without being punished and, yes, she can buy her own food, still baffled her to this day. (And she is grateful to them for taking her in)
